    source: 'Original',
    text: 'The starting gun hadn\'t even faded when Marcus felt the old tightness grip his chest. Lane four. The worst lane in the world, he had decided — not too close to the inside, not far enough out to see the whole pack. Just stuck, sandwiched between boys who had been training since they could walk. He studied their faces as they shook out their legs and rolled their necks. None of them looked nervous. He tucked that fact away carefully, like something he might need later.\n\nHe had been running since dawn. Not on the track — on the canal towpath behind his estate, where the tarmac was cracked and the weeds pushed through like stubborn green fists. His trainers were wrong, too. Everyone else wore spikes, those sharp little teeth biting into the red surface. Marcus wore the white cross-trainers his mum had bought from the market stall on Saturday, still faintly smelling of the plastic wrapping. He had thought about asking to borrow a pair of spikes from school but the PE office was always locked and anyway he hadn\'t been sure how to ask.\n\nRound the first bend, he was sixth. Not terrible. The boy in the yellow vest from Northfield Academy pulled ahead with long, easy strides, as if he were simply out for a morning stroll and the rest of them were in his way. Marcus watched the gap open — two metres, then four — and felt something harden in his stomach. Not despair. Something older and quieter than that.\n\nBy the back straight, he had moved to fourth. He didn\'t know how. His body had made the decision without consulting him, lengthening his stride on the softer surface beyond the final bend, finding a rhythm in the crowd noise that rose and fell like breathing. The wind came at him sideways, cold and blunt, filling his mouth.\n\nThird. The boy in yellow was still ahead, but the gap had changed shape somehow — it no longer looked like a door being shut. It looked like a distance that could be crossed.\n\nHe thought of the towpath. He thought of the mornings before school when the mist sat low over the water and there was no one to watch or judge, just the sound of his feet and his own ragged breath keeping time. He hadn\'t trained for this race. He had trained for something else entirely — for the simple, private pleasure of moving fast through a quiet world. No coaches, no stopwatches, no one calling split times from the side of a track. Just him and the grey water and the sound of birds he couldn\'t name.\n\nThe bend arrived. He leaned into it, letting his arms drive. He could hear the boy in yellow breathing now, could almost count the exhales. The finish line was a white stripe a hundred metres away and beyond it the blur of faces in the stand, colour and sound fusing into something almost musical.\n\nHe crossed first. For one full second he didn\'t understand what had happened. Then the noise reached him, and he stopped running, and bent over his knees, and the world rushed back in — the smell of cut grass and liniment, the sharp scratch of the track beneath his market-stall trainers, the crowd still making their incomprehensible, wonderful sound.',
