    source: 'Original',
    text: 'At home, she was Priya. At school, she was Priya too — but a different one, a slightly flattened version, like a photograph of a photograph, the colours one shade off.\n\nHer mother called her name the proper way, the syllables round and full, the r sitting low in the throat, warm as something held in cupped hands. Mrs Hargreaves called it with a short i, sharp as a needle, and smiled as if she had done something generous. Priya had stopped correcting her in Year 5. It was easier to be the name that came out of other people\'s mouths. Easier and duller and, after a while, so familiar that she had almost stopped noticing the difference herself.\n\nThe new girl arrived in February, which was the worst month for it. The heating was broken, the sky was the colour of old concrete, and everyone already had their people. Her name was Amara, and she sat beside Priya in science because the only free stool was the one with the wobbly leg. Neither of them mentioned it.\n\nThey didn\'t speak for a week. Then Amara knocked Priya\'s pencil case off the bench with her elbow, said \'sorry\' in a way that sounded like a question, and Priya said \'it\'s fine\' in a way that meant it. After that, something shifted.\n\n\'Do they say your name right?\' Amara asked one lunch time, out of nowhere, looking straight ahead at the grey school field.\n\nPriya thought about Mrs Hargreaves\'s generous smile. \'Not really,\' she said.\n\n\'Mine either. They put the stress on the wrong syllable. Makes me sound like someone else.\'\n\nThey sat with that for a moment. The wind moved through the bare trees at the field\'s edge, and somewhere behind them, a group of boys were arguing about football in loud, happy voices.\n\n\'What do they call you at home?\' Amara asked.\n\nPriya said her own name — the real one, the round one, her mother\'s version — and felt something unknot in her chest. It was the first time she had said it at school. It sounded, in the cold air, like reclaiming something she hadn\'t known was lost.\n\nAmara said her own name too. The stress landed in the right place, and Priya felt the difference the way you feel a room warm up — not all at once, but certainly.\n\nThey had a system by March. They used the flattened names with teachers, the real ones with each other. It was a small geography — two different countries that only they could see on the map, sharing one set of coordinates. Strange, Priya thought, that a name could be a place you went to or a place you were kept from. She had never thought of it that way before. Now she couldn\'t think of it any other way.\n\nOn the last day of term, Mrs Hargreaves called the register and said \'Priya\' with her short i, and Priya said \'here\' and glanced sideways, and Amara was already looking at her with a small, private smile — not about the mispronunciation, but about the knowing. About the fact that there were two of them, now, who knew the difference.',
