        model: 'Model answer: I strongly agree that the writer creates a powerful sense of in-between-ness, though what makes it particularly effective is how ordinary it is. The experience is not dramatised through conflict or confrontation — instead it lives in small surrenders: stopping corrections in Year 5, becoming \'a slightly flattened version.\' The cumulative weight of years is captured in that single phrase, and the reader understands without being told how long Priya has carried this. The photography metaphor is especially precise: a copy of a copy does not look broken, it just looks slightly wrong, which is exactly the texture of the experience being described. I also found the geography metaphor — \'two different countries that only they could see on the map\' — very effective, because it reframes in-between-ness not as exclusion but as a kind of secret richness. The writer is careful not to let this become tragedy: the final image of the \'private smile\' suggests that finding one person who understands can be enough. This complicates but deepens the loneliness rather than erasing it, making the reader feel both the loss and the small triumph simultaneously.'
