    id: 'Y8F18',
    title: 'The Revision Timetable',
    type: 'fiction',
    source: 'Original',
    text: 'Jade had colour-coded it in six different highlighters. The timetable stretched across three sheets of A4, taped together with surgical precision on the wall above her desk, Monday to Sunday, 7 a.m. to 10 p.m. Every subject had its own shade. Maths was orange. History was green. English was purple, which she had chosen on purpose because purple felt serious. She had even drawn small icons beside each block: a ruler for maths, a leaf for biology, a tiny quill for English. The icons had taken forty minutes.\n\nIt had taken two hours to make. She had not yet revised for a single second.\n\nThis was what she did not tell her mother, who came to the door at half eight with a mug of hot chocolate and said \'How\'s it going?\' in the careful voice she used when she meant something else entirely. \'Fine,\' Jade said, which was not a lie, exactly. The timetable looked marvellous.\n\nThe problem was the silence. When she sat down and opened the maths textbook, the silence of the house gathered itself around her like something alive. She could hear the boiler clicking, the neighbour\'s television murmuring through the wall, the particular sound of her own breathing. It was unbearable in a way she could not fully explain. The numbers on the page sat still and waited for her to do something. She read the same equation three times and understood less each time.\n\nShe rang Cleo at nine o\'clock.\n\n\'Are you revising?\' Cleo asked immediately.\n\n\'Yes,\' Jade said. Then: \'No. I\'ve made a timetable.\'\n\n\'How many colours?\'\n\n\'Six.\'\n\nThere was a pause she recognised — the pause of someone trying not to laugh. \'I\'ve made a playlist,\' Cleo said finally. \'It\'s called "Study Vibes" and it\'s mostly Beyoncé.\'\n\n\'Is Beyoncé helping?\'\n\n\'She is not.\'\n\nThey stayed on the phone for half an hour, technically revising — Cleo recited dates from the French Revolution while Jade read quadratic equations aloud and neither of them retained a single fact. But there was comfort in it, the shared uselessness, the way failing at a thing together felt entirely different from failing at it alone.\n\nAt ten past ten, Jade\'s mother knocked again. \'Lights out in twenty.\'\n\nJade looked at the timetable. Tuesday was pink for biology and she had done precisely none of it. The pink sat there, bright and accusing, like a question she hadn\'t answered. She thought about peeling the whole thing off the wall. She thought about starting again tomorrow with a simpler version, maybe just three colours.\n\nInstead, she opened the biology textbook to chapter one and read four pages. They were not good pages — the diagrams were complicated and the sentences were long — but she read them, and when she got to the end she folded the corner down, which felt, inexplicably, like a small act of courage.\n\nShe fell asleep with the light on and dreamed of nothing in particular, and in the morning the timetable was still there, its six colours waiting patiently, as if they had all the time in the world.',
