        model: 'Model answer: The writer structures the passage so that Jade\'s progress is barely visible — almost accidental — which makes it feel true rather than triumphant. It opens with the timetable in full satirical glory, two hours of preparation for nothing, immediately establishing Jade\'s talent for productive displacement. The central phone call with Cleo is structurally important as a turning point in tone: the dialogue is warm and self-aware, and the phrase \'failing at a thing together felt entirely different from failing at it alone\' signals that Jade is growing in self-understanding even as she procrastinates. After this, the structure returns to solitude, and the shift is subtle: she considers quitting but instead reads four pages. The writer places this small act at the end of the narrative and calls it \'a small act of courage,\' a deliberate structural understatement that asks the reader to measure progress against Jade\'s own scale, not anyone else\'s. The final image of the timetable \'waiting patiently\' closes the passage gently, releasing the tension without fully resolving it.'
