    id: 'Y8F19',
    title: 'The Clockmaker\'s Shop',
    type: 'fiction',
    source: 'Original',
    text: 'Detective Inspector Ros Kaur had been in enough rooms to know when one was hiding something. The clockmaker\'s shop was hiding several things at once.\n\nThe clocks, first of all. Three hundred and forty-two of them, she had been told — every wall, every shelf, every surface occupied. At ten past two in the afternoon they ticked in a fractured unison, slightly out of step with one another, so that the sound was not one sound but a crowd of sounds pressing from every direction. Constable Yates stood in the doorway looking faintly nauseous. She understood why. There was something about so many instruments measuring time that made you feel, absurdly, that time was being watched.\n\n\'He lived here,\' she said. It was not a question.\n\nYates consulted his notebook. \'Mr Edmund Thrale. Seventy-one. Sole owner since 1987. Neighbours say they hadn\'t seen him in about a week. Post had backed up.\' He paused. \'Quite a lot of post.\'\n\nRos moved into the room, careful not to touch anything. The smell was dust and machine oil and something else she couldn\'t name — metallic, faint, like old coins left in a drawer. The shop floor was immaculate, swept clean, not a gear or spring out of place. The counter was not. Spread across it, among the small tools and clockwork innards, were three things that did not belong: a pair of white cotton gloves, a folded piece of paper, and a key that was clearly not a clock key.\n\nShe did not touch the key. She took a photograph instead, moving her phone slowly to capture the angle. The key was brass, long-handled, with a double-bit head. Not a shop key. Not a house key. Something for a strong-box, or a gate, or a room that was not this room.\n\n\'Have you looked upstairs?\' she asked.\n\n\'Not yet.\' A beat. \'There are a lot of clocks upstairs as well.\'\n\nThe folded paper was harder to ignore. She photographed it from four angles, then, pulling a fresh glove from her pocket, she unfolded it. Inside, in a cramped, precise hand, were seven names. Not a list she recognised. Not addresses, not phone numbers — just names, each with a small symbol beside it. Six names had a single horizontal line drawn through them. The seventh did not.\n\nRos refolded the paper and set it back precisely where it had been. She stood for a moment among the ticking, which had begun, she imagined, to arrange itself into something she almost understood.\n\n\'Bag all three,\' she said. \'The key, the gloves, the paper. And I want the lock on the upstairs door checked for fresh marks. If there\'s a strongbox up there, I want it found before the end of the afternoon.\'\n\nYates was already writing. \'What do you think it is?\'\n\nRos looked at the seventh name. The one still unmarked. The one that was, perhaps, still waiting for its line.\n\n\'A list of some kind,\' she said. \'The question is what you get crossed off it for.\'',
